33:02.355 --> 33:05.472
You know, I'm miserable.
I don't think anyone would care.

33:05.567 --> 33:07.023
I'll care.

33:07.402 --> 33:09.734
But you're a loser,
which doesn't really count.

33:09.863 --> 33:13.230
Things are gonna be okay.

33:13.325 --> 33:14.405
They are?

33:14.493 --> 33:16.825
Yeah. You're gonna meet someone.

33:16.912 --> 33:18.823
You're gonna be happy.

33:23.001 --> 33:24.332
I shouldn't kill myself?

33:24.419 --> 33:26.080
Definitely not.

33:29.090 --> 33:31.832
Okay, so I don't need to kill myself.

33:33.386 --> 33:35.672
Wow! I thought...

33:35.764 --> 33:38.927
I thought that like... That suffocation idea,

33:39.059 --> 33:41.596
I thought that was like
a really good idea, you know?

33:41.686 --> 33:42.675
It wasn't.

33:42.771 --> 33:43.851
Wow!

33:46.107 --> 33:48.018
My night's opened up.

33:49.277 --> 33:51.689
Do you wanna hang out or something?

33:51.780 --> 33:53.441
Oh, not really.

33:53.573 --> 33:55.859
It's all right. It's okay.

33:55.951 --> 33:58.533
No! Good idea.

33:59.412 --> 34:02.620
Let's hang out. I'll see you tonight.

34:02.707 --> 34:04.572
I'll see you tonight.

34:05.794 --> 34:07.204
FRANK: Cool, okay.

34:07.879 --> 34:09.460
(SLOW POP MUSIC PLAYING)

34:20.809 --> 34:22.639
(INAUDIBLE)

34:35.407 --> 34:38.399
(INAUDIBLE)

35:00.056 --> 35:01.341
(INAUDIBLE)

35:10.859 --> 35:12.474
(INAUDIBLE)

35:32.839 --> 35:34.375
(INAUDIBLE)

35:48.188 --> 35:49.724
(INAUDIBLE)

36:00.241 --> 36:01.856
(PHONE RINGING)

36:04.037 --> 36:05.117
Hello, this is Anna.

36:05.205 --> 36:06.285
Hi, it's Mark.

36:06.790 --> 36:09.202
Oh! Hi, Mark. Didn't you get my e-mail?

36:09.542 --> 36:11.157
The one about not being
good enough for you?

36:11.252 --> 36:12.287
That's the one.

36:12.379 --> 36:14.165
Yeah, got that, cheers.

36:14.255 --> 36:18.624
Listen, the reason I'm calling is
I want to ask you out on another date.

36:20.553 --> 36:21.588
Why would you do that?

36:21.680 --> 36:25.969
Well, I found out I can pretty much
have my life the way I want it.

36:26.351 --> 36:28.387
Congratulations! I gotta go.

36:28.478 --> 36:29.513
No, wait.

36:29.604 --> 36:33.813
Listen, I know you said you didn't wanna go
on another date with me, ever,

36:33.900 --> 36:38.485
but I'm different now.
I think I'm in your league.

36:38.571 --> 36:39.651
Are you better looking?

36:39.739 --> 36:43.402
No. More powerful.
I think you have to see it for yourself.

36:43.493 --> 36:44.528
Have you been to the gym?

36:44.619 --> 36:50.285
No. I joined a gym, but just...
Things have changed for me.

36:50.375 --> 36:51.615
I think you'll hardly recognise me.

36:51.710 --> 36:52.790
Did you buy new clothes?

36:52.877 --> 36:55.835
No. Sorry, can we just meet up? It'd be best.

36:55.922 --> 36:59.380
You did admit yourself that,
you know, we got on.

36:59.467 --> 37:04.257
If you had an okay time, then please say yes.

37:04.347 --> 37:08.010
I'm just asking for
one teensy, weensy little date.

37:10.562 --> 37:11.972
Okay, fine.

37:12.188 --> 37:13.428
Fantastic.

37:15.024 --> 37:18.391
I'll pick you up tomorrow, about 8:00?

37:18.486 --> 37:21.978
Most likely, though, this will be our last date,
so just know that.

37:22.073 --> 37:23.938
Yeah. Great.

37:24.033 --> 37:25.068
Okay. Bye!

37:26.578 --> 37:27.784
Bye!

37:27.871 --> 37:29.281
Hang up, Mark.

37:29.372 --> 37:30.407
Bye.

37:35.670 --> 37:38.537
MALE NARRATOR: ...proudly presents
The Industrial Revolution.

37:38.631 --> 37:41.589
Hello, I'm Angelo Badsmith.

37:41.676 --> 37:44.634
Come, watch me read
about the exciting events

37:44.721 --> 37:47.428
that took place during
the Industrial Revolution,

37:47.515 --> 37:52.305
written by the most beloved and esteemed
screenwriter of his generation,

37:52.395 --> 37:54.101
Brad Kessler.

37:54.189 --> 37:58.649
I don't think anyone can write
a better screenplay than Brad Kessler.

38:03.364 --> 38:04.399
No?

38:29.307 --> 38:30.672
BRAD: Hey!

38:30.767 --> 38:33.224
Did you come to beg for your job back?

38:33.311 --> 38:34.517
Everybody!

38:34.604 --> 38:36.310
That's the loser that thought
the Black Plague

38:36.397 --> 38:37.682
would make an interesting film.

38:37.774 --> 38:39.981
Hey! Good luck, douche bag.

38:42.529 --> 38:44.861
-You can't go in there.
-I've got an appointment.

38:44.948 --> 38:46.813
Oh, then go right in.

38:47.992 --> 38:49.948
Talk to you later.

38:50.995 --> 38:53.611
Hi. That was the head of the studio.

38:56.292 --> 38:58.374
Why are you here?

38:58.461 --> 39:03.376
Well, when you fired me,
I was seriously depressed.

39:04.092 --> 39:05.832
-I knew it.
-But...

39:06.386 --> 39:09.469
I went for a walk, right out of town.

39:09.556 --> 39:14.266
And I came across a desert,
and I fell asleep under a tree, palm tree.

39:14.352 --> 39:17.810
I don't do well
with other people's life-changing stories.

39:17.897 --> 39:22.186
And then when I woke up,
I saw like a thing sticking out of the sand.

39:22.277 --> 39:26.896
And I unearthed it,
and it was an ancient chest.

39:26.990 --> 39:29.356
Really old. Seven hundred years old.

39:29.450 --> 39:33.284
And in that chest was this.

39:33.371 --> 39:34.451
What is it?

39:34.539 --> 39:37.827
It's a never-before-heard event from history.

39:38.585 --> 39:40.291
When does it take place?

39:40.378 --> 39:41.493
1300s.

39:41.588 --> 39:42.998
Oh, come on, no, Mark!

39:43.089 --> 39:46.923
Mark, I've already told you,
we don't do Black Plague movies here!

39:47.010 --> 39:51.003
It's not about the Black Plague!
It's not just about the Black Plague.

39:51.097 --> 39:54.055
It's about... Can I just read it, please?

39:54.767 --> 39:57.383
Get excited. Don't tap, get excited.

39:57.478 --> 39:58.843
Get very excited,

39:58.938 --> 40:05.434
because this is one of the best discoveries

40:05.528 --> 40:08.691
man has ever discovered.

40:08.781 --> 40:10.021
And you can be part of it.

40:10.116 --> 40:12.732
Yes, but is there a movie there?

40:12.827 --> 40:16.445
The greatest movie
Lecture Films has ever made.

40:18.374 --> 40:19.955
Start reading.

40:22.128 --> 40:27.668
"On the very first day of the 14th century,
a momentous occasion occurred.

40:27.759 --> 40:33.550
"It began like any other day.
The sun rose, babies began to cry.

40:33.640 --> 40:37.053
"But all of that was interrupted
when a giant, flying spaceship

40:37.143 --> 40:41.978
"crashed down from the skies
and landed in the heart of Babylon."

40:42.065 --> 40:43.100
What?

40:47.111 --> 40:50.820
Uh... Get everyone in here, right now.
We got a big one.

40:50.907 --> 40:53.068
Oh, please, Mark, continue.

40:56.704 --> 40:59.821
MARK: "The ninja army
unleashed a giant fireball

40:59.916 --> 41:03.909
"and brought the robot dinosaur
to its knees, saving Mars, Earth

41:04.045 --> 41:08.505
"and the nude Amazonian alien women,
all in one sweeping motion.

41:08.591 --> 41:10.377
"The Earth was saved.

41:10.468 --> 41:14.882
"Jebediah and Aleena were allowed to marry
by alien King Wanglor.

41:14.973 --> 41:18.591
"It was to be the first human
nude Amazonian alien woman wedding,

41:18.726 --> 41:20.887
"and no expense would be spared.

41:20.979 --> 41:24.346
"All of Babylon and Mars were invited
to join the celebrations.

41:24.440 --> 41:27.147
"The wedding was held
on a brisk summer's day on Mars.

41:27.235 --> 41:29.021
"And all of the survivors
of the Great Ninja War

41:29.112 --> 41:30.818
"and the Black Plague were present.

41:30.905 --> 41:35.274
"They feasted and danced and laughed,
and it was a joyous occasion.

41:35.410 --> 41:37.025
"The moment the bride and groom kissed,

41:37.120 --> 41:40.487
"King Wanglor performed
a mind-wipe on all the humans,

41:40.581 --> 41:44.494
"thereby erasing all knowledge
of these events for about 700 years,

41:44.585 --> 41:48.123
"until one day,
a great writer by the name of Mark Bellison

41:48.256 --> 41:53.592
"would stumble across them in the desert
after being fired by his crap boss, Anthony,

41:55.596 --> 42:00.681
"and mocked by Brad and Shelley,
two huge douche bags.

42:01.602 --> 42:06.096
"Lecture Films would go on to make
the picture, and it'd be a huge success.

42:06.190 --> 42:09.853
"And Mark would become very wealthy
and famous from it."

42:22.165 --> 42:24.781
What are you gonna call this, Mark?

42:27.045 --> 42:28.160
The Black Plague.

42:28.296 --> 42:29.957
(ALL EXCLAIMING)

42:31.966 --> 42:34.423
I want you to start immediately
'cause I think this could be

42:34.510 --> 42:36.671
the best screenplay ever written.

42:36.804 --> 42:38.465
Oh, it will.

42:38.556 --> 42:42.970
It will be the best screenplay
ever written by anyone.

42:52.528 --> 42:53.813
Well...

42:55.031 --> 42:57.522
I guess congratulations
on selling your script today.

42:57.658 --> 42:59.740
-Cheers.
-Cheers.

43:01.996 --> 43:05.113
Tell me something about your family.
I don't know that much about you.

43:05.208 --> 43:06.448
(MARK EXHALES)

43:06.542 --> 43:09.329
We're sort of what you'd call unlucky.

43:09.420 --> 43:10.785
My dad was an alcoholic.

43:10.880 --> 43:12.086
Sad.

43:12.173 --> 43:16.257
Drinking got to a point where he lost his job,
and with a family to support,

43:16.344 --> 43:18.380
he had no choice
but to turn to a life of crime.

43:18.513 --> 43:20.049
What kind of crime?

43:20.181 --> 43:23.048
Burglary. Houses, mainly.

43:30.399 --> 43:31.479
What are you doing here?

43:31.567 --> 43:33.523
It's Monday at noon.
You're not supposed to be at home now.

43:33.611 --> 43:35.602
If you must know,
I'm incredibly stressed at work.

43:35.696 --> 43:37.732
I've come home early.
I'm having a bit of me time.

43:37.865 --> 43:39.230
More importantly, what are you doing?

43:39.367 --> 43:40.982
Well, I was gonna rob your house.

43:41.077 --> 43:42.408
I don't like that idea. Not a fan of that at all.

43:42.537 --> 43:44.277
Well, I'm not gonna do it now
because you're in.

43:44.372 --> 43:45.452
And do you know what's gonna happen?

43:45.540 --> 43:47.030
I'm gonna call the police,
you're gonna be arrested.

43:47.125 --> 43:48.786
Well, I'm just gonna leave,
and you don't know my name.

43:48.876 --> 43:50.207
-What is your name?
-Richard Bellison.

43:50.294 --> 43:51.704
(LAUGHING) Good to meet you.

43:51.796 --> 43:54.833
You've got two options. Option one,
I send the police to your house, right?

43:54.924 --> 43:57.256
Arrest you there,
embarrass you in front of your neighbours.

43:57.385 --> 43:59.797
Or option two, you just come in
and wait for the police here.

43:59.887 --> 44:02.048
-No, I'll wait.
-Yeah?

44:02.140 --> 44:04.597
-Come on in then. Do you want a cup of tea?
-Yeah, that'd be great.

44:04.725 --> 44:06.886
MARK: He spent the last years
of his life in jail.

44:07.562 --> 44:08.847
I never really knew him.

44:08.938 --> 44:13.102
But I've been blessed
with some luck as well in my life.

44:13.234 --> 44:14.974
I had a wonderful mother who raised me.

44:15.069 --> 44:17.776
-Oh, that's sweet.
-She's great.

44:17.905 --> 44:18.894
Where is she?

44:19.031 --> 44:21.067
At an old people's home.

44:21.701 --> 44:24.943
But I'm gonna get her out of there tomorrow.

44:26.038 --> 44:27.073
I'm gonna get her a mansion,

44:27.206 --> 44:29.071
so she can spend
the rest of her life in luxury.

44:29.208 --> 44:30.698
That's nice.

44:32.086 --> 44:34.202
-Compliments from the chef.
-Thank you.

44:34.297 --> 44:36.709
I don't know what's wrong with him today,
but these just look awful.

44:36.799 --> 44:37.879
They look fine to me.

44:37.967 --> 44:39.878
Well, you're stupid.

44:45.933 --> 44:47.093
I was thinking.

44:47.226 --> 44:51.310
Now I'm obviously rich and successful and...

44:51.439 --> 44:58.402
Maybe I'm in your league
and that we could be together, romantically.

44:59.572 --> 45:01.608
What would be the point?

45:03.284 --> 45:05.070
We might enjoy it.

45:07.955 --> 45:11.789
Well, I do like you
and I do enjoy your company.

45:11.918 --> 45:13.749
And if we were to get together and procreate,

45:13.836 --> 45:16.919
I would like the offspring
that are carrying half my genetic code

45:17.006 --> 45:20.544
to be well taken care of, financially stable.

45:20.635 --> 45:24.344
I also think you'd make a good father
and a good husband, which I like.

45:24.472 --> 45:25.803
Fantastic.

45:27.016 --> 45:29.098
Unfortunately, none of that changes the fact

45:29.185 --> 45:33.770
that you'd still be contributing
half the genetic code to our children.

45:36.275 --> 45:39.813
I don't want little fat kids with snub noses.

45:41.614 --> 45:42.820
Sure.

45:44.867 --> 45:46.107
(CELL PHONE RINGING)

45:46.202 --> 45:47.487
Sorry.

45:48.162 --> 45:50.198
Hello? Speaking.

45:52.667 --> 45:53.622
She what?

45:55.670 --> 45:56.955
Mum?

45:57.046 --> 45:59.788
They just called me. What's going on?

46:00.174 --> 46:03.712
They said I'm probably gonna die tonight.

46:03.844 --> 46:05.004
What?

46:05.137 --> 46:07.253
Hello, there.
I was just coming in to check on her.

46:07.348 --> 46:08.633
You must be Martha's son.

46:08.724 --> 46:09.930
What do you mean, she's gonna die tonight?

46:10.017 --> 46:12.884
It does not look very good.
She suffered a major heart attack.

46:13.020 --> 46:16.763
Her heart is very weak.
Her pulse is not very strong.

46:16.857 --> 46:19.724
Her blood pressure is dropping rapidly,

46:19.860 --> 46:24.729
and she will probably suffer
a fatal heart attack sometime tonight.

46:24.865 --> 46:27.902
Yes. Still going to die.

46:30.913 --> 46:32.574
Side note,

46:32.707 --> 46:36.120
it's fajita night downstairs in the cafeteria,

46:36.210 --> 46:40.249
so you might wanna grab yourself
a little bite down there after Mom dies.

46:40.381 --> 46:41.541
Okay?

46:47.096 --> 46:50.008
I'm so scared, Mark.

46:50.099 --> 46:55.389
People don't talk about it,
but death is a horrible thing.

46:56.230 --> 46:58.687
One minute, you're alive,

47:00.026 --> 47:02.768
and then just like that, it's all gone.

47:05.448 --> 47:07.188
This is it, Mark.

47:08.909 --> 47:12.242
Few more hours like this and then

47:15.374 --> 47:18.116
an eternity of nothingness.

47:21.088 --> 47:22.077
(GASPS)

47:22.423 --> 47:23.629
(MONITOR BEEPING)

47:23.758 --> 47:24.964
Nurse!

47:29.347 --> 47:31.383
Her vitals are dropping.

47:32.016 --> 47:35.099
I'm so... I'm so frightened.

47:37.188 --> 47:38.428
Oh, Mum.

47:46.447 --> 47:49.109
Mum, listen to me.

47:49.784 --> 47:51.445
Listen carefully.

47:51.786 --> 47:54.949
You're wrong about
what happens after you die.

47:57.124 --> 47:59.035
It's not an eternity of nothingness.

47:59.126 --> 48:00.286
Huh?

48:01.962 --> 48:05.295
You go to your favourite place
in the whole world.

48:05.800 --> 48:10.965
Yeah. And everyone you've ever loved
and who's ever loved you will be there.

48:11.097 --> 48:12.712
And you'll be young again.

48:12.807 --> 48:16.140
You'll run and jump
like you used to and dance.

48:16.227 --> 48:17.967
You used to dance.

48:21.816 --> 48:23.556
There's no pain.

48:28.322 --> 48:29.778
Just love.

48:33.285 --> 48:34.650
Happiness.

48:35.996 --> 48:38.328
And everyone gets a mansion.

48:39.333 --> 48:42.621
And it lasts for an eternity. An eternity, Mum.

48:48.008 --> 48:50.090
Say hello to Dad for me.

48:51.512 --> 48:53.298
Tell him I love him.

49:00.980 --> 49:03.141
-Go on.
-What else happens?

49:03.858 --> 49:05.018
Mum.

49:05.693 --> 49:08.355
I'm gonna see my mother again when I die.

49:08.446 --> 49:10.778
Will you tell us more, please?

49:10.865 --> 49:12.275
(MONITOR BEEPING)

49:12.366 --> 49:13.856
(MONITOR FLAT-LINING)

49:14.869 --> 49:16.109
(SOBS)

50:43.624 --> 50:44.739
Hi.

50:45.376 --> 50:46.491
Hi.

51:30.546 --> 51:32.332
(CROWD CHATTERING)

51:44.768 --> 51:48.511
Excuse me. Excuse me. Excuse me.
Excuse me. Excuse me. Excuse me.

51:50.149 --> 51:51.434
There he is! That's him!

51:51.525 --> 51:53.311
(CROWD CLAMOURING)

51:54.486 --> 51:56.351
Is there only one place you go when you die?

51:56.447 --> 51:58.312
Will everyone who has ever died be there?

51:58.407 --> 51:59.487
What's this place called?

51:59.575 --> 52:01.156
Will I get to have sex with people there?

52:01.243 --> 52:02.449
Are there shopping malls?

52:02.536 --> 52:04.527
What about smoking?
Can we smoke up there?

52:04.622 --> 52:06.237
(PHONE RINGING)

52:06.832 --> 52:07.912
Hi.

52:08.000 --> 52:11.117
They're saying you know something different
about what happens after you die.

52:13.213 --> 52:17.547
Twenty four hours ago, Mark Bellison
was just your typical nobody writer.

52:17.635 --> 52:20.377
Today, people are saying
he has new information

52:20.471 --> 52:23.008
about what happens after you die.

52:23.349 --> 52:24.930
Oh, this is bad.

52:25.017 --> 52:28.384
I just need to get... I know, I'm sorry.
Pardon me. Pardon me, please.

52:28.479 --> 52:31.312
Oopsie! Excuse me. Um, oh, excuse me.

52:31.398 --> 52:32.433
(CHUCKLES)

52:32.900 --> 52:34.140
Quick.

52:34.276 --> 52:35.561
Come in.

52:36.236 --> 52:37.442
Yeah.

52:40.949 --> 52:42.780
Just tell me what you told your mom.

52:42.868 --> 52:44.733
I don't think I should. Anything can happen.

52:44.828 --> 52:47.786
I've got to keep my mouth shut from now on.
Why did I...

52:47.873 --> 52:50.831
Whatever you said
obviously affected a lot of people.

52:50.918 --> 52:52.579
I mean, I don't think you have
the choice to keep it in.

52:52.670 --> 52:54.331
Yes, I do. I could walk out that door now.

52:54.463 --> 52:57.045
I could get on the first plane to Namibia.
No one knows me there.

52:57.132 --> 53:00.750
Just tell me what you said, Mark.
Please, just tell me.

53:00.844 --> 53:04.803
My mum was dying, she was scared,
she was shaking all over,

53:04.890 --> 53:08.257
and she said she didn't want to
just enter a world of nothingness.

53:08.352 --> 53:12.186
So I said, "You're wrong about what happens
after you die."

53:12.690 --> 53:14.772
And I told her, I said,

53:15.776 --> 53:17.607
"It's not a world of nothingness.

53:17.695 --> 53:20.732
"You go to the best place ever,
where all your friends are

53:22.825 --> 53:24.190
"and you have an eternity of joy."

53:25.994 --> 53:27.734
I made her happy.

53:32.918 --> 53:34.704
How do you know these things?

53:34.795 --> 53:36.205
Well, I...

53:37.256 --> 53:39.292
Oh, that makes me happy.

53:40.551 --> 53:43.714
You have to tell them everything you know.
You have to. It's too big.

53:43.804 --> 53:46.136
Listen to me, you don't understand.
The things I told my mum...

53:46.265 --> 53:48.677
Didn't you say that it made her happy
to hear them?

53:48.767 --> 53:50.598
-Yes.
-And how did that make you feel?

53:50.686 --> 53:52.392
-Good.
-So imagine how it would feel

53:52.479 --> 53:55.312
to do the same for all of these people.

54:01.363 --> 54:02.728
Uh, okay.

54:04.783 --> 54:06.489
I need some time.

54:09.079 --> 54:11.286
You sure I should do this?

54:12.124 --> 54:13.864
Of course you should.

54:13.959 --> 54:17.793
Mark, what you know
is gonna change mankind forever.

54:19.131 --> 54:22.168
It's the most important thing
the world has ever heard.

54:25.596 --> 54:27.382
I'll let you work.

54:39.610 --> 54:41.020
(KNOCKING ON DOOR)

54:41.153 --> 54:42.689
MARK: Come in.

54:44.948 --> 54:46.609
I brought pizza.

54:47.367 --> 54:49.198
How come you never told me
we all get mansions?

54:49.286 --> 54:50.776
-Uh, I didn't...
-Just let him keep working.

54:50.871 --> 54:52.611
It's one thing that you invented
the bicycle, but...

54:52.706 --> 54:54.947
Just keep working, don't worry about...

54:55.042 --> 54:58.034
I've known him for a long time,
and he never told me that.

54:59.630 --> 55:03.043
-I got plain, and I got...
-That's good.

55:03.217 --> 55:06.801
I got another plain.

55:09.556 --> 55:11.547
MALE REPORTER: In London, England,
they wait.

55:11.683 --> 55:16.552
In Rome, Italy, they wait.
In New York City, they wait.

55:16.688 --> 55:18.804
The world has come to a standstill,

55:18.899 --> 55:21.140
with everyone
at their televisions and radios,

55:21.235 --> 55:22.896
or here on this lawn,

55:23.028 --> 55:27.067
waiting for Mark Bellison to come forth
and tell the people what he knows.

55:43.757 --> 55:44.872
Oh!

55:46.552 --> 55:47.667
Hi.

55:50.389 --> 55:51.925
I've finished.

55:54.268 --> 55:55.678
Are you ready?

55:56.937 --> 55:58.427
-I guess so.
-Oh.

55:58.522 --> 56:02.106
I wish I had something better
to put these on, though, like tablets.

56:02.192 --> 56:04.353
Or just even better paper.

56:10.075 --> 56:12.157
-That feels better.
-Good.

56:12.911 --> 56:13.946
SHELLEY: Just...

56:14.955 --> 56:16.695
Just tell them what you know.

56:16.790 --> 56:19.748
-GREG: Good luck out there, man.
-Cheers.

56:30.804 --> 56:31.793
REPORTER: Twenty four hours ago,

56:31.930 --> 56:34.717
Mark Bellison was just
your typical nobody writer.

56:34.808 --> 56:37.720
Today, people are saying
he has new information

56:37.811 --> 56:40.473
about what happens after you die.

56:56.121 --> 56:57.611
ANNA: Sorry.

57:00.959 --> 57:02.324
I guess

57:03.170 --> 57:07.664
you heard about the stuff
that I told my mum the other night.

57:07.966 --> 57:09.877
That's why you're here.

57:10.010 --> 57:12.171
I know some things,
some very important things

57:12.304 --> 57:15.137
about what happens to you after you die.

57:16.725 --> 57:19.011
Everything you need to know

57:19.144 --> 57:21.556
is written on these pizza boxes.

57:31.114 --> 57:32.604
"Number one,

57:33.033 --> 57:36.696
"there is a man in the sky
who controls everything.

57:38.538 --> 57:41.075
-"Number two..."
-Whoa, whoa, whoa, whoa.

57:41.208 --> 57:42.744
What does he look like?

57:42.876 --> 57:47.119
Uh, tall, big hands for making stuff.
Good head of hair.

57:47.214 --> 57:48.454
What ethnicity is he?

57:48.548 --> 57:52.006
Uh, he's a new type of ethnicity.

57:52.094 --> 57:55.211
He's a mixture of all our ethnicities.

57:55.305 --> 57:56.715
-Does he live in the clouds?
-No.

57:56.807 --> 57:58.138
-Can we see him?
-MARK: No.

57:58.225 --> 58:00.841
He lives higher than the clouds,
too high to see him.

58:00.936 --> 58:03.268
-So he lives in space.
-Not that high.

58:03.397 --> 58:04.512
So then the thermosphere?

58:04.606 --> 58:08.394
MARK: Sorry, people. I've got a lot
to get through here. Can we just...

58:08.819 --> 58:13.313
Man lives in the sky, you can't see him.
He controls everything. Cool?

58:13.490 --> 58:15.572
Good. "Number two,

58:15.742 --> 58:19.610
"when you die, you don't disappear
into an eternity of nothingness.

58:19.746 --> 58:22.579
"Instead, you go to a really great place."

58:22.666 --> 58:23.746
(CROWD EXCLAIMING APPROVINGLY)

58:23.834 --> 58:25.040
MARK: "Number three,

58:25.127 --> 58:28.585
"in that place, everyone will get a mansion."

58:28.672 --> 58:30.378
(CROWD LAUGHING)

58:30.465 --> 58:32.171
(CROWD APPLAUDING)

58:34.302 --> 58:38.045
-What kind of mansion?
-The best mansion you could think of.

58:38.140 --> 58:40.256
Ah, I was thinking of a horrible mansion!

58:40.350 --> 58:41.635
Well, no.

58:41.768 --> 58:44.225
It's the best mansion you could ever think of.

58:44.312 --> 58:47.395
Not the one you're thinking of
right now, but ever.

58:47.482 --> 58:51.896
Whatever the best mansion is you'd like,
that's the one you're gonna get.

58:51.987 --> 58:53.693
(CLEARING THROAT) "Number four,

58:53.780 --> 58:56.692
"when you die,
all the people you love will be there."

58:56.783 --> 58:57.943
Will they have their own mansions?

58:58.035 --> 59:00.401
Yeah. Of course. Everyone gets a mansion.

59:00.495 --> 59:01.655
What if I want them to live in my mansion?

59:01.747 --> 59:05.365
Well, that's fine. They'll leave their mansion.
They'll come and live with you, won't they?

59:05.459 --> 59:08.622
-What happens to their mansion?
-I don't know. It goes back on the market.

59:08.712 --> 59:10.794
Can we... "Number five,

59:10.881 --> 59:12.166
(SIGHS)

59:12.257 --> 59:16.170
"when you die, there will be free ice cream
for everyone.

59:16.428 --> 59:20.797
"All day and all night,
whatever flavours you can think of."

59:21.183 --> 59:23.720
-Even bad flavours?
-Why would you think of bad flavours?

59:23.810 --> 59:25.801
You just said every flavour I could think of.

59:25.896 --> 59:28.683
Oh, no. I just thought of vanilla and skunks.

59:28.774 --> 59:29.980
Well, don't eat that, then.

59:30.067 --> 59:32.183
I just thought
that chocolate sauce was diarrhoea.

59:32.277 --> 59:35.861
Don't put that on the ice cream, then!
What is the matter with you people?

59:35.947 --> 59:38.654
Can we... Please. "Number six,

59:38.742 --> 59:42.200
"if you do bad things, you won't get to go
to this great place when you die."

59:42.287 --> 59:44.073
Where will you go?

59:44.623 --> 59:47.160
A terrible place, the worst place imaginable.

59:47.250 --> 59:49.081
What constitutes a bad thing?

59:49.169 --> 59:52.127
Awful crimes, rape, murder, things like that.

59:52.214 --> 59:54.045
-Is punching someone bad?
-Yes.

59:54.132 --> 59:56.839
-What if they're trying to hurt you?
-Well, then it's fine.

59:56.927 --> 59:58.383
-Is cursing bad?
-No.

59:58.470 --> 01:00:00.802
-What about being late for work?
-MARK: No, that's...

01:00:00.889 --> 01:00:04.552
I mean, you might lose your job
if the boss doesn't like it,

01:00:04.643 --> 01:00:06.679
but it won't affect what happens
to you after you die.

01:00:06.770 --> 01:00:09.762
What about if you forget to feed your dog?

01:00:10.023 --> 01:00:12.184
MARK: Well, then, if you forget,
I mean, it's bad for the dog.

01:00:12.275 --> 01:00:16.359
If the dog dies, it's bad, but it's not...
I mean, don't do it on purpose.

01:00:16.446 --> 01:00:20.564
Don't buy a dog just to starve it
for a laugh, but... Can we...

01:00:20.659 --> 01:00:23.867
If I do just one bad thing,
do I go to the bad place?

01:00:23.954 --> 01:00:25.069
No!

01:00:26.706 --> 01:00:28.867
You get three chances.

01:00:29.417 --> 01:00:31.533
Three bad things and you're out.

01:00:31.628 --> 01:00:32.708
Like baseball!

01:00:32.796 --> 01:00:34.036
(CROWD EXCLAIMS)

01:00:34.131 --> 01:00:36.873
Sort of. So, anything else?

01:00:37.050 --> 01:00:38.085
ALL: Yeah!

01:00:38.176 --> 01:00:41.168
-Oh, please, can we just move on?
-MAN: No!

01:00:41.513 --> 01:00:43.094
We have to know everything that's bad.

01:00:43.181 --> 01:00:44.671
CROWD: Yeah.

01:00:44.766 --> 01:00:46.131
(ALL CLAMOURING)

01:00:47.144 --> 01:00:48.224
Fine.

01:00:48.311 --> 01:00:49.642
Is it bad to wear pants?

01:00:49.813 --> 01:00:51.428
Oh. What the...

01:00:53.608 --> 01:00:58.944
No. There is no hairstyle
that can put you in the bad place.

01:00:59.030 --> 01:01:00.395
We've been through this.

01:01:00.490 --> 01:01:05.655
The main ones are things like hurting people
physically, on purpose, okay?

01:01:05.745 --> 01:01:09.988
Taking their stuff, doing things
to people they don't want done,

01:01:10.083 --> 01:01:12.620
murdering people on purpose.

01:01:13.170 --> 01:01:15.001
Okay. "Number nine,

01:01:15.589 --> 01:01:17.921
"the man in the sky who controls everything

01:01:18.008 --> 01:01:21.045
"decides if you go to the good place
or the bad place.

01:01:21.136 --> 01:01:23.627
"He also decides who lives and who dies."

01:01:23.722 --> 01:01:25.929
-Does he cause natural disasters?
-Yes.

01:01:26.474 --> 01:01:29.341
-Did he cause my mom to get cancer?
-Yes.

01:01:29.436 --> 01:01:31.927
Did he cause that tree to land
on my car last week?

01:01:32.022 --> 01:01:35.389
-Yeah.
-Did he kill my dad with that heart attack?

01:01:38.153 --> 01:01:39.233
Yeah.

01:01:39.321 --> 01:01:41.937
(CROWD EXCLAIMING IN DISAPPOINTMENT)

01:01:44.618 --> 01:01:46.279
I say fuck the man that lives in the sky!

01:01:46.411 --> 01:01:48.117
(CROWD CHEERING)

01:01:50.040 --> 01:01:51.200
Yeah, that guy's evil!

01:01:51.291 --> 01:01:54.533
That guy's a coward, hiding up there
doing bad things to us.

01:01:54.628 --> 01:01:55.788
Why doesn't he do it to our faces?

01:01:55.879 --> 01:01:58.461
We have to stop that evil bastard
before he kills us all!

01:01:58.590 --> 01:02:00.251
(CROWD CHEERING)

01:02:02.802 --> 01:02:04.918
MARK: Wait, wait, listen.

01:02:05.972 --> 01:02:10.215
The man who lives in the sky
and controls everything

01:02:10.310 --> 01:02:13.222
is also responsible for
all the good stuff that happens.

01:02:13.313 --> 01:02:14.553
(CROWD EXCLAIMING APPROVINGLY)

01:02:14.648 --> 01:02:18.232
He's the guy that saved my life
on that fishing trip when the boat capsized?

01:02:18.318 --> 01:02:20.650
-Yes.
-Did he capsize the boat?

01:02:20.987 --> 01:02:22.067
Yeah.

01:02:22.155 --> 01:02:24.897
He killed my grandmother
and left me those millions of dollars?

01:02:24.991 --> 01:02:26.447
You bet yeah.

01:02:26.576 --> 01:02:29.784
So, he's the one
who cured my mom's cancer?

01:02:30.121 --> 01:02:31.327
Yeah.

01:02:31.498 --> 01:02:35.662
So, he's kind of a good guy,
but he's also kind of a prick, too.

01:02:35.752 --> 01:02:38.744
Yeah. Right, but check this out, okay?

01:02:38.838 --> 01:02:42.831
"Number ten, even if the man in the sky
does bad stuff to you,

01:02:42.968 --> 01:02:47.177
"he makes up for it by giving you
an eternity of good stuff after you die."

01:02:47.305 --> 01:02:49.341
(CROWD EXCLAIMING IN SATISFACTION)

01:02:49.474 --> 01:02:52.841
As long as you don't do any of that
bad stuff that you mentioned, right?

01:02:52.978 --> 01:02:55.765
-Yeah, of course.
-So it's kind of a test.

01:02:56.022 --> 01:02:57.102
Yeah.

01:02:57.190 --> 01:02:59.522
Well, that's everything I know.

01:02:59.609 --> 01:03:01.349
(CROWD APPLAUDING)

01:03:07.534 --> 01:03:10.025
How do you know all these things?

01:03:10.161 --> 01:03:12.322
Because the man in the sky told me.

01:03:12.414 --> 01:03:14.826
Yeah, well, how come we're just finding out
about these things now,

01:03:14.916 --> 01:03:17.328
millions of years into our existence?

01:03:17.419 --> 01:03:20.832
(SOFTLY) I don't know. He forgot.
Got... Seen all the stuff he does?

01:03:21.047 --> 01:03:22.412
Thank you.

01:03:22.549 --> 01:03:23.538
(CROWD CLAMOURING)

01:03:29.472 --> 01:03:31.383
Think that went well.

01:03:33.560 --> 01:03:35.892
(CHEERFUL POP MUSIC PLAYING)

01:03:59.753 --> 01:04:00.788
(INAUDIBLE)

01:04:23.276 --> 01:04:25.392
(INAUDIBLE)

01:04:53.723 --> 01:04:55.088
(INAUDIBLE)

01:05:00.814 --> 01:05:03.851
Cheers, cheers.

01:05:03.942 --> 01:05:05.898
(CROWD CLAMOURING)

01:05:11.116 --> 01:05:12.731
(FANS CHEERING)

01:05:33.346 --> 01:05:35.007
-Cheers.
-Cheers.

01:05:46.526 --> 01:05:51.771
Did I ever tell you about the time
I saved a baby from a burning building

01:05:51.865 --> 01:05:54.527
and there was a bear, and...

01:05:54.617 --> 01:05:56.027
Wait, there was a burning building
and a bear?

01:05:56.119 --> 01:06:02.206
Yeah, well, I heard a baby crying
and so I ran in there through the flames,

01:06:02.292 --> 01:06:06.035
not caring about my own safety,
got the baby, jumped out.

01:06:06.129 --> 01:06:07.869
It was the second storey, jumped out.

01:06:07.964 --> 01:06:08.999
(MIMICS THUD)

01:06:09.090 --> 01:06:11.297
I landed, baby safe. But then this bear...

01:06:11.384 --> 01:06:13.090
-Wait, how did you survive?
-Well, let me tell you.

01:06:13.178 --> 01:06:14.918
No, how did you survive the jump?

01:06:15.013 --> 01:06:16.844
I've seen you twist your ankle
crossing the street.

01:06:16.931 --> 01:06:21.265
Because on this occasion
I landed in something soft.

01:06:21.352 --> 01:06:22.387
-Oh.
-So...

01:06:22.479 --> 01:06:23.810
What did you land in?

01:06:23.897 --> 01:06:25.228
-Jam.
-Jam.

01:06:25.315 --> 01:06:29.308
It was a barrel of jam.
It was a jam factory on fire.

01:06:29.402 --> 01:06:30.892
Probably what attracted the bear
in the first place.

01:06:30.987 --> 01:06:33.228
-Right.
-You haven't heard of that?

01:06:33.656 --> 01:06:37.274
The burning building, baby,
bear, factory, jam incident?

01:06:37.368 --> 01:06:38.483
Shoot, no.

01:06:38.578 --> 01:06:41.365
Yeah, classic. So, I land.

01:06:41.581 --> 01:06:45.324
This bear is coming toward,
big, lumbering, eating machine

01:06:45.418 --> 01:06:47.830
Iike that happy chap over there.

01:06:47.921 --> 01:06:49.912
-What, sleeping, ugly fatty?
-Well...

01:06:50.006 --> 01:06:52.088
-He's not happy.
-Well, how do you know?

01:06:52.675 --> 01:06:55.667
What do you mean?
Look at him. He's a loser.

01:06:56.763 --> 01:06:59.254
MARK: You can't tell that
from just looking at the guy.

01:06:59.349 --> 01:07:02.091
He could be the world's greatest poet.

01:07:02.685 --> 01:07:04.596
Well, he probably is a loser. Bad example.

01:07:04.729 --> 01:07:08.096
But I'm saying, it doesn't have to be,
just by...

01:07:09.025 --> 01:07:11.687
Okay. What do you see
when you see this fellow here?

01:07:11.778 --> 01:07:13.109
ANNA: Short, sweaty, bald guy.

01:07:13.196 --> 01:07:14.606
-Right.
-Hi!

01:07:15.406 --> 01:07:17.112
MARK: He's carrying a briefcase.
He's in a hurry.

01:07:17.242 --> 01:07:19.858
He's probably off to
a really important meeting.

01:07:19.953 --> 01:07:22.114
He's probably a high-powered businessman.

01:07:22.247 --> 01:07:24.033
You see more than I do.

01:07:24.123 --> 01:07:26.705
Well, because, if you look...

01:07:27.794 --> 01:07:29.785
What do you see when you see those guys?

01:07:29.921 --> 01:07:31.286
ANNA: Mmm...

01:07:31.631 --> 01:07:35.123
Two nerdy losers in hats?

01:07:35.301 --> 01:07:38.919
Yeah. Good. Good observational skills.

01:07:39.097 --> 01:07:45.093
But what I mean is, look beyond
just their appearance and look at them.

01:07:45.562 --> 01:07:48.304
They're holding hands. They're in love.

01:07:52.485 --> 01:07:54.646
Hey, do me.

01:07:54.988 --> 01:07:58.230
I mean, just what do you see?
What do you see in me?

01:07:58.324 --> 01:08:00.610
You're pretty.

01:08:01.077 --> 01:08:02.237
You've got a wonderful smile.

01:08:02.328 --> 01:08:05.820
-Well, that's what everyone sees.
-I wasn't finished.

01:08:06.749 --> 01:08:09.912
You're the sweetest,
most caring person I know.

01:08:10.003 --> 01:08:13.166
And you've got a freckle there
I've never told you about how much I love.

01:08:13.298 --> 01:08:15.084
You usually smile,

01:08:15.174 --> 01:08:18.837
but sometimes you spend your day in bed,
eating and crying.

01:08:18.970 --> 01:08:22.133
You'll hold someone's hand
after their mum...

01:08:25.143 --> 01:08:28.305
You're the most wonderful person
I've ever met.

01:08:32.984 --> 01:08:35.566
What do you see when you look at me?

01:08:40.867 --> 01:08:43.700
You're chubby and you have a snub nose.

01:08:45.496 --> 01:08:47.157
Yeah. That's about it.

01:08:47.372 --> 01:08:49.033
(CHUCKLES SOFTLY)

01:08:52.920 --> 01:08:54.410
You're smart.

01:08:56.506 --> 01:08:57.917
You're kind.

01:08:58.843 --> 01:09:01.550
You're the sweetest man I've ever met.

01:09:02.388 --> 01:09:06.221
You are definitely
the most interesting person I know.

01:09:06.392 --> 01:09:08.553
And you are fun to be with.

01:09:09.228 --> 01:09:11.560
And you see the world in a way
that nobody else sees the world,

01:09:11.689 --> 01:09:14.395
and I like the way you see the world.

01:09:15.234 --> 01:09:17.395
And you're my best friend.

01:09:17.904 --> 01:09:21.192
You make me happier
than anyone I've ever known.

01:09:29.791 --> 01:09:32.624
-Why can't we be together, then?
-Because of the whole genetics thing.

01:09:32.752 --> 01:09:35.209
Little fat kids with snub noses.

01:09:38.591 --> 01:09:43.051
It's a shame that being rich and famous
doesn't change your genetics.

01:09:44.596 --> 01:09:46.428
Because I love you.

01:09:49.810 --> 01:09:53.520
Does being rich and famous
change your genetic material?

01:10:01.280 --> 01:10:02.315
No.

01:10:02.865 --> 01:10:07.655
It doesn't. Our kids would be
little fat things with snub noses.

01:10:13.876 --> 01:10:16.538
BOB: (ON RADIO) Thanks for that, Jim.
Next up, Mark Bellison.

01:10:16.629 --> 01:10:17.664
Does he deserve all the money and fame

01:10:17.797 --> 01:10:20.834
or is he just some fat loser
who hears things from the man in the sky?

01:10:20.967 --> 01:10:22.082
JIM: I say fat loser, Bob.

01:10:22.176 --> 01:10:24.838
BOB: It's as simple as this, Jim.
